97 Our fullest information about the aqueductu of Rome is derived from Sex. Julius Frontinus, who was curator aquaram from 97 till 106 Α.Ῑ>., under Nerva and Trajan. He says that in the time of N erva there were nine aqueducts at Rome. Procopius (500-565 Am.) says that in his time fonrteen aqueducts were still preserved at Rome (Bell. Goth. l, 19). It seems probable that he has fixed the number too high, by counting as separate aqueducts in some cases what were merely branchos. The full number of separate aqueductu seems to have been eleven. There is, however, no doubt that their number and magnitude were such as to fully justify what Pliny the Elder (23-79 am.) says of one of them—namely, the Claudian, H.
